The optical properties of the water solutions of the as-prepared carbon nanodots from o-phenylendiamine were also studied. The UV–visible absorption of the aqueous solution of CNDs (10 ppm) is depicted in Fig. S4 and clearly shows that the absorption bands of the CNDs are at 235 nm and 280 nm which are attributed to the π- π* transition of the conjugated CC units and the n- π* transition of CO groups on the surface of CNDs, respectively [44,50]. The results confirm the graphite structure of CNDs showing the typical absorption peak of an aromatic π system which is similar to that of polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons [51]. The fluorescence spectra of CNDs at different excitation wavelengths are illustrated in Fig. 1
                            in which the emission maxima peak is at 517 nm with the excitation wavelength of 430 nm. Considering the particle size distribution of the as-prepared CNDs (about 2 nm) obtained from the dynamic light scattering analysis (Fig. 2
                           ), the strong emission in the visible light region is related to the quantum-sized graphite structure of carbon nanodots. These quantum-sized graphite structures have a narrow band gap energy which could be used as a powerful energy-transfer component in photocatalyst design [51]. The quantum yield of CNDs with yellow emission was estimated to be about 56% in the excitation wavelength of 430 nm.
